WEBVTT

00:30.000 --> 00:39.240
Hello and welcome to Veterans of the Valley.

00:39.240 --> 00:41.560
I'm Tom Turbivill.

00:41.560 --> 00:46.280
Some call it the forgotten war, but Norman Beale of rural Brass' County has not forgotten

00:46.280 --> 00:52.880
a thing about his second battalion, Fifth Marine's assault on the Korean coast in 1950.

00:52.880 --> 00:57.560
Nor has he forgotten the horror and the cold of that winter, scaling the cliffs at the

00:57.560 --> 00:59.160
beaches at Inchan.

00:59.200 --> 01:03.880
The card game that he lost that kept him in Korea to fight even longer, the Korean

01:03.880 --> 01:08.760
war cost 54,000 American lives and another 8,000 were missing.

01:08.760 --> 01:13.360
Norman Beale counts himself very lucky to have survived to tell his story of service.

01:13.360 --> 01:17.120
Please welcome Norman Beale of Edge to Veterans of the Valley.

01:17.120 --> 01:21.880
Mr. Beale, it's not her to have you on Veterans of the Valley and thank you first for your service.

01:21.880 --> 01:23.600
You are a local kid all the way.

01:23.600 --> 01:30.400
You grew up in Brian, you graduated from Allen Academy in 1948 and want to move right

01:30.400 --> 01:36.120
along because you joined the Marine Corps soon after you graduated from high school in 1948.

01:36.120 --> 01:41.560
So take us from there and your service in the Marine Corps and how that got you overseas

01:41.560 --> 01:43.560
to Korea.

01:43.560 --> 01:51.960
Well, I was overseas in other places also for a couple of years and came back to the states

01:51.960 --> 01:58.280
and a few months later we had to turn around and go back.

01:58.280 --> 02:09.160
But we didn't in the Marine Corps at that time in 1948 only had about 75,000 Marines.

02:09.160 --> 02:10.160
Right.

02:10.160 --> 02:18.520
So they had to scrape all over the world and get more Marines to develop a brigade.

02:18.520 --> 02:29.640
One of my colleagues was calling for Marines early and all we could gather up was one brigade

02:29.640 --> 02:35.320
and each battalion was missing one company.

02:35.320 --> 02:41.480
And the company that we did have only had two cartoons.

02:41.480 --> 02:42.480
Right.

02:42.480 --> 02:43.480
So that was...

02:43.480 --> 02:44.480
Right.

02:44.480 --> 02:49.840
And the military had really changed because it was after World War II and the military

02:49.840 --> 02:52.440
was kind of scaling down at that time.

02:52.440 --> 02:53.440
Very much so.

02:53.440 --> 02:57.920
You talked about how the military had changed during this time between World War II and before

02:57.920 --> 02:59.440
the Korean War broke out.

02:59.440 --> 03:06.120
Now after World War II all future wars were going to be push buttons.

03:06.120 --> 03:12.640
And so the Air Force decided they didn't need too many Army personnel.

03:12.640 --> 03:20.400
They didn't need the Marines but the Navy, they wanted to keep the Navy.

03:20.400 --> 03:21.400
Right.

03:21.400 --> 03:22.400
Right.

03:22.400 --> 03:25.320
You had spent a long time on a boat.

03:25.320 --> 03:29.640
I know you'd gone out to the Mariana Islands and the West Pacific for your training and

03:29.640 --> 03:34.960
you came home, said you'd never get on a boat again but that was wrong because Korean war

03:34.960 --> 03:37.120
broke out and you were headed to Korea.

03:37.120 --> 03:41.840
I didn't want to get in on any more stinking shit.

03:42.640 --> 03:45.960
You talk highly about the training that you got because you said that a lot of the

03:45.960 --> 03:53.960
NCOs and the officers were World War II veterans who were certainly war experienced themselves.

03:53.960 --> 03:56.600
So you did get some good training from these folks.

03:56.600 --> 04:00.800
Yes and just the Marine Corps trains all the time.

04:00.800 --> 04:01.800
Right.

04:01.800 --> 04:08.160
I finally got back to the States and I got out of the Fleet Marine Force and was put

04:08.160 --> 04:14.440
in a company that didn't go in the field.

04:14.440 --> 04:22.000
So our new colonel decided we were getting soft and after I was there about three weeks

04:22.000 --> 04:24.160
we were putting the field again.

04:24.160 --> 04:25.160
Right.

04:25.160 --> 04:27.840
I learned how to dig foxholes again.

04:27.840 --> 04:29.240
And you would need that later on.

04:29.240 --> 04:34.320
Obviously, second battalion, fifth Marines, this is one of the oldest outfits dating back

04:34.320 --> 04:35.920
to World War I.

04:35.920 --> 04:40.240
As a matter of fact, I looked up it was a German soldiers that actually gave them the nickname

04:40.240 --> 04:44.920
the devil dogs because they were so tough fighting in World War I in 1918.

04:44.920 --> 04:45.920
Bellowwood.

04:45.920 --> 04:46.920
That's right.

04:46.920 --> 04:47.920
That's right.

04:47.920 --> 04:51.640
So this was part of the outfit that you were in.

04:51.640 --> 04:58.800
You left San Diego, August of 1950 and thought you were going to stop over in Japan but you

04:58.800 --> 05:02.240
went straight to the coast of Korea to Busan.

05:02.240 --> 05:03.240
Talk about that.

05:03.240 --> 05:07.760
It wasn't much of South Korea left.

05:07.760 --> 05:09.320
That's why we didn't stop.

05:09.320 --> 05:10.320
Right.

05:10.320 --> 05:17.280
And when we got to Busan, Korea, our general was down on the dock.

05:17.280 --> 05:23.160
He wanted to know if Colonel Murray had gotten his message.

05:23.160 --> 05:28.400
And Murray called out and said, no sir.

05:28.400 --> 05:35.240
And he said, well, you get off the ship now and let's move on to the front.

05:35.240 --> 05:36.240
Right.

05:36.240 --> 05:38.880
And that was his message that we didn't get.

05:38.880 --> 05:39.880
Right.

05:39.880 --> 05:48.680
But fortunately, we spent that whole night unloading the ship and early the next morning we

05:48.680 --> 05:51.080
moved forward.

05:51.080 --> 05:52.760
So you didn't stick around long.

05:52.760 --> 05:54.120
You were headed to the front.

05:54.120 --> 05:55.120
Right.

05:55.120 --> 05:56.720
And talk about that.

05:56.720 --> 06:01.720
Talk about your first venture into combat heading towards North Korea.

06:01.720 --> 06:02.720
What you recall about that.

06:02.720 --> 06:03.880
Because you're still a young kid.

06:03.880 --> 06:10.960
I mean, you're a young kid from the country and it's quite a change in your life, obviously.

06:10.960 --> 06:18.440
We were down in South Korea and like I say, we were pushed into combat right away on August

06:18.440 --> 06:20.960
the 7th.

06:20.960 --> 06:23.040
We attacked.

06:23.040 --> 06:28.640
And that was the same date that the offensive action in World War II.

06:28.640 --> 06:35.040
August the 7th of the Gwata Canal, the first Marine vision, which the 5th Marines was

06:35.040 --> 06:37.040
part of.

06:37.040 --> 06:38.040
Right.

06:38.040 --> 06:46.440
And after a couple of few days, we had pushed the North Koreans back 30 miles, 30 plus

06:46.440 --> 06:47.440
miles.

06:47.440 --> 06:48.240
Right.

06:48.240 --> 06:53.120
And the very next day or two, we were called back down South.

06:53.120 --> 06:56.960
They could not protect our sides.

06:56.960 --> 07:03.560
And then we put what we call the fire brigade.

07:03.560 --> 07:08.760
We moved from one spot to another, trying to hold the North Koreans back.

07:08.760 --> 07:09.760
Right.

07:09.760 --> 07:14.960
We had two major battles on the NACTON River.

07:14.960 --> 07:21.320
The first NACTON, we pushed them back over the river and we all went down and rested

07:21.320 --> 07:24.200
two days or three days.

07:24.200 --> 07:34.240
And we were called back up because we had lost or the military had lost the NACTON front

07:34.240 --> 07:35.240
again.

07:35.240 --> 07:37.440
It was called the NACTON Bulls.

07:37.440 --> 07:38.440
Right.

07:38.440 --> 07:40.880
The 6th North Korean People's Army.

07:40.880 --> 07:41.880
Right.

07:41.880 --> 07:48.780
The first of his day they had come from Seoul, the capital all the way down to this little

07:48.780 --> 07:50.920
area down in Busan.

07:50.920 --> 07:54.160
We call it the Busan perimeter.

07:54.160 --> 08:01.720
And they had not hit anything, but they found a new breed of cat down there.

08:01.720 --> 08:02.720
Right.

08:02.720 --> 08:03.720
And so.

08:03.720 --> 08:04.720
Go ahead.

08:04.720 --> 08:14.440
Then we were pulled off the NACTON and all of a sudden we went down to Seoul, Busan.

08:14.440 --> 08:21.080
And we got on board ship and we thought maybe we could get to go back to Japan for our

08:21.080 --> 08:22.080
and our duty.

08:22.080 --> 08:23.520
Because you done such a good job.

08:23.520 --> 08:25.800
Because we had done such a good job.

08:25.800 --> 08:30.800
But I looked at one morning and there were ships and there were directions.

08:30.800 --> 08:37.880
And then they come on the intercom and they told us that we had been selected to hit the

08:37.880 --> 08:41.160
North Koreans right in the throat.

08:41.160 --> 08:46.240
We were going to make an in-chon landing at Seoul.

08:46.240 --> 08:50.560
Seoul was about 30 something miles from In-chon.

08:50.560 --> 08:51.560
Right.

08:51.560 --> 09:00.760
But when we got to In-chon, all of the Navy were bombarding in-chon for people.

09:00.760 --> 09:07.660
And our planes were coming over and strafing and bombing and didn't see how anybody could

09:07.660 --> 09:08.660
live.

09:08.660 --> 09:19.320
But anyway, one of our battagons had to take a small island right out from In-chon.

09:19.320 --> 09:22.240
It had a causeway going in to In-chon.

09:22.240 --> 09:23.240
Right.

09:23.240 --> 09:24.240
Right.

09:24.240 --> 09:25.240
This was Womito Island.

09:25.240 --> 09:26.240
Is that right?

09:26.240 --> 09:27.240
Is that what you told me?

09:27.240 --> 09:29.080
I believe that's what you told me the other day.

09:29.080 --> 09:30.080
Womito.

09:30.080 --> 09:31.080
There we go.

09:31.080 --> 09:32.080
I was close.

09:32.080 --> 09:36.080
It had a causeway actually from the island to the mainland.

09:36.080 --> 09:38.080
Yes, to the mainland.

09:38.080 --> 09:39.080
Right.

09:39.080 --> 09:46.320
And the third battalion had to set up on that highway and keep from attacking on the way.

09:46.320 --> 09:48.320
But the island was armed with North Koreans.

09:48.320 --> 09:49.320
Yes, yes.

09:49.320 --> 09:50.320
Right.

09:50.320 --> 09:52.560
And we pretty well wiped them out.

09:52.560 --> 09:56.160
Our third battalion pretty well wiped them all out.

09:56.160 --> 09:57.160
Right.

09:57.160 --> 09:58.160
And we were witnessing this.

09:58.160 --> 09:59.560
Were you still on the boat or had you?

09:59.560 --> 10:00.560
I was still on the boat.

10:00.560 --> 10:02.160
You were still on the ship?

10:02.160 --> 10:03.160
Yes.

10:03.160 --> 10:04.160
Two.

10:04.160 --> 10:05.160
We had two battalion still.

10:05.160 --> 10:08.960
We had got our third battalion, finally.

10:08.960 --> 10:09.960
Right.

10:09.960 --> 10:10.960
And we were on board.

10:10.960 --> 10:24.380
Now the reason we were on board in Korea, they had one of the highest water up 30, the

10:24.380 --> 10:26.980
tide of 30 feet.

10:26.980 --> 10:29.380
And then it would drop.

10:29.380 --> 10:33.820
And after it dropped, there was just a huge mud flat out there.

10:33.820 --> 10:35.620
And our ships were in the mud.

10:35.620 --> 10:36.620
Right.

10:36.620 --> 10:38.700
Still shooting.

10:38.700 --> 10:43.740
So we had ladders that the Navy had fixed for us.

10:43.740 --> 10:47.420
And we crawled up a seawall.

10:47.420 --> 10:54.100
And when we got off the seawall, my own gunnery sergeant was walking up and down.

10:54.100 --> 11:02.260
And as you know, a gunnery sergeant in the Marine Corps has used his words that I wouldn't

11:02.260 --> 11:04.740
repeat right now.

11:04.740 --> 11:06.300
That's why he's a gunnery sergeant.

11:06.300 --> 11:07.300
That's right.

11:07.300 --> 11:08.300
Get off the beach.

11:08.300 --> 11:09.300
Get off the beach.

11:09.300 --> 11:14.500
And we captured our in-chon pretty quick.

11:14.500 --> 11:15.500
Excuse me.

11:15.500 --> 11:16.500
I can get mixed up.

11:16.500 --> 11:17.500
Right.

11:17.500 --> 11:22.140
And as soon as we did do, we started for so.

11:22.140 --> 11:26.260
Now you're all, I want the viewers to be able to picture this.

11:26.260 --> 11:27.260
You're on foot.

11:27.260 --> 11:28.260
Yes.

11:28.260 --> 11:29.260
Right.

11:29.260 --> 11:32.460
What kind of weaponry did you personally have?

11:32.460 --> 11:35.260
I started out with the machine gun.

11:35.260 --> 11:42.380
And been later on, I got the car being and I got rid of it as soon as I couldn't, got

11:42.380 --> 11:44.700
an M1 rifle.

11:44.700 --> 11:45.700
Right.

11:45.700 --> 11:47.540
And the very good rifle.

11:47.540 --> 11:48.540
Right.

11:48.540 --> 11:49.540
Oh yeah.

11:49.540 --> 11:52.060
I know.

11:52.060 --> 11:54.140
So you're marching and you're battling?

11:54.140 --> 11:56.060
Well, we're battling.

11:56.060 --> 11:58.780
And because this is what the war was all about.

11:58.780 --> 11:59.780
That's what we got.

11:59.780 --> 12:08.940
We captured Kimpo Airfield, which was one of any tarmacs there other than few knockdown

12:08.940 --> 12:10.780
yaks.

12:10.780 --> 12:17.620
And we made another landing after we captured the air base.

12:17.620 --> 12:26.780
We crossed the Han River in LCVP's landing craft.

12:26.780 --> 12:32.900
We made it across and then we headed to Seoul.

12:32.900 --> 12:39.380
My battalion did not go down our regiment, did not go down into the city of Seoul.

12:39.380 --> 12:43.460
That was the first regiment with Chester Pillar and his group.

12:43.460 --> 12:44.460
Right.

12:44.460 --> 12:47.820
And Chester Pillar, he was the most decorated soldier of the Korean War.

12:47.820 --> 12:49.820
He was most decorated Marine.

12:49.820 --> 12:50.820
Marine, excuse me, yes.

12:50.820 --> 13:00.580
Of the Korean War, of Wars, he was fought in the Banana Wars and all the way up.

13:00.580 --> 13:01.820
That was a good outfit.

13:01.820 --> 13:02.820
Right.

13:02.820 --> 13:08.220
He was one who said, we've got the enemy in front of us and we've got him in back of us.

13:08.220 --> 13:09.980
And we've got him on each side.

13:09.980 --> 13:14.260
We've got him right where we won't, he can't get away now.

13:14.260 --> 13:16.260
And he was about right.

13:16.260 --> 13:24.660
I know that you're reluctant to talk specifically about, as you refer to, the blood and guts

13:24.660 --> 13:25.660
of war.

13:25.660 --> 13:27.300
And I understand that.

13:27.300 --> 13:33.020
But what were your thoughts about what you were seeing?

13:33.020 --> 13:34.340
Were you frightened?

13:34.340 --> 13:40.620
Did your training kick in when it needed to?

13:40.620 --> 13:43.820
What were your thoughts about life and death at that time that you recall?

13:43.820 --> 13:52.580
Well, if you're in combat, you're afraid until you go into the attack or until the enemy

13:52.580 --> 13:54.220
goes into an attack.

13:54.220 --> 13:59.420
So then you get fairly calm.

13:59.420 --> 14:04.740
We had some horrible battles down in the perimeter, Pusan perimeter.

14:04.740 --> 14:05.740
Right.

14:05.740 --> 14:12.020
But when we got on board ship, we went up, Tenchon, captured the capital.

14:12.020 --> 14:19.220
So we went back down, got on board ship, surely it's our own arduous.

14:19.220 --> 14:26.260
But we went all the way around the peninsula of Korea to the east side of North Korea.

14:26.260 --> 14:27.260
Right.

14:27.260 --> 14:29.220
The place called Wonson.

14:29.220 --> 14:38.260
It was more of an administrative movement into the city of Wonson.

14:38.260 --> 14:39.260
Right.

14:39.260 --> 14:49.020
And then a day or two later we got on board train, flat cars starting to get in cold.

14:49.020 --> 14:51.340
And we headed north.

14:51.340 --> 14:57.620
One of the things that really had us worried, we went to a long, long tunnel.

14:57.620 --> 15:04.740
And fortunately the North Koreans were not thinking about that tunnel.

15:04.740 --> 15:09.500
We went on up to Haggaroo, North Korea.

15:09.500 --> 15:18.700
And then we headed north, headed for the Chosin reservoir area.

15:18.700 --> 15:25.380
And just before we got to the mountains, we had mountains on top of mountains.

15:25.380 --> 15:37.420
We got on board a very small, small, cow track going up into North Korea, up into the

15:37.420 --> 15:38.900
reservoir area.

15:38.900 --> 15:39.900
Yes, sir.

15:39.900 --> 15:46.540
When we got up there, I think I have heard, I don't know if anybody that had a thermometer.

15:46.540 --> 15:53.420
But I heard that when we got to the top it was 13, over 13 degrees below zero.

15:53.420 --> 15:56.300
And that was a physiological shock.

15:56.300 --> 15:57.300
All that.

15:57.300 --> 16:01.500
And thank goodness no one attacked that night.

16:01.500 --> 16:08.180
Stayed there a few days and then the seventh regiment and the fifth regiment moved up

16:08.180 --> 16:16.420
to Haggaroo, North Korea, which was right at the bottom of the big reservoir.

16:16.420 --> 16:24.020
Our regiment went up the right side, or the east side, and the there too.

16:24.020 --> 16:27.820
We had thanks even.

16:27.820 --> 16:30.420
And it kind of warmed up.

16:30.420 --> 16:34.940
But we were only there just three or four days.

16:34.940 --> 16:45.900
And we started down because two regiment, our partial regiment, of the seventh Army division

16:46.300 --> 16:51.180
came up to the right side and took our place.

16:51.180 --> 16:54.340
They were pretty well slaughtered later.

16:54.340 --> 16:57.900
I think our 800 got out.

16:57.900 --> 16:58.900
Right.

16:58.900 --> 17:04.380
Let's pause right there and let's look at some photographs of some of the things we're

17:04.380 --> 17:08.180
talking about because you have mentioned how cold it became.

17:08.180 --> 17:13.180
And we've got some photographs that depict 30 and 40 below.

17:13.180 --> 17:14.180
Right.

17:14.180 --> 17:17.980
And some pictures first off, this is you and your older brothers.

17:17.980 --> 17:19.940
You're the baby of the family, you're on the left.

17:19.940 --> 17:20.940
That's correct.

17:20.940 --> 17:22.740
And these are your brothers.

17:22.740 --> 17:23.740
Right.

17:23.740 --> 17:27.860
Who were they from, say from right to left as we're looking at it?

