And I believe these are not Marines here.

20:36.660 --> 20:38.660
There's some Marines in the ditch there.

20:38.660 --> 20:40.660
Yes, sir.

20:40.660 --> 20:45.460
But he didn't like that photograph, but yeah, it was used on a stamp.

20:45.460 --> 20:46.460
Right.

20:46.460 --> 20:47.460
Right.

20:47.460 --> 20:48.460
That's that picture.

20:48.460 --> 20:49.780
Incredible photograph.

20:49.780 --> 20:52.580
There you are.

20:52.580 --> 20:57.460
As you were fixing to be able to come home.

20:57.460 --> 20:58.460
Right.

20:58.460 --> 21:01.780
You've grown yourself a little pretty good looking stash there.

21:01.780 --> 21:02.780
Right.

21:02.780 --> 21:04.660
I don't know how I got away with it.

21:04.660 --> 21:06.580
Bring the court and put it up with that.

21:06.580 --> 21:11.620
But you told the story about that if you wanted to go R and R to Japan, you had to get

21:11.620 --> 21:14.660
that shaved off and you were the first to get your shaved off.

21:14.660 --> 21:15.660
It came off immediately.

21:15.660 --> 21:17.860
Yeah, I bet it did.

21:17.860 --> 21:23.020
I was standing right next to one of my men on board shift.

21:23.020 --> 21:25.780
And I was making comments.

21:25.780 --> 21:30.860
He turned around and looked at me and he said, Bill, is that you?

21:30.860 --> 21:32.360
Without the beard.

21:32.360 --> 21:34.380
Move on to the next.

21:34.380 --> 21:36.860
This is a...

21:36.860 --> 21:37.860
Those are prisoners.

21:37.860 --> 21:38.860
Yeah.

21:38.860 --> 21:45.780
This is a newspaper that comes out, this was spring of 84 called the Chosen Few of this

21:45.780 --> 21:51.020
sort of a publication that is about your unit.

21:51.020 --> 21:53.260
You know what I'm going to add there.

21:53.260 --> 21:54.260
Excuse me.

21:54.260 --> 21:56.500
I'm going to talk to a torture today.

21:56.500 --> 21:58.500
Yes, sir.

21:58.500 --> 22:03.660
We got the word that you do not mistreat any, any misogyr.

22:03.660 --> 22:06.060
We want them to come out with our hands up.

22:06.060 --> 22:07.060
Yes, sir.

22:07.060 --> 22:10.180
Not too many of them did, but some of them did.

22:10.180 --> 22:11.180
Right.

22:11.180 --> 22:13.180
Move on to...

22:13.180 --> 22:15.220
Now tell me, this is you on the right.

22:15.220 --> 22:19.980
Tell me about the person on the left and this is a person that you actually...

22:19.980 --> 22:20.980
This is me.

22:20.980 --> 22:21.980
So it's out of a foxhole, right?

22:21.980 --> 22:22.980
Right.

22:22.980 --> 22:23.980
Is this Mr. Dixon?

22:23.980 --> 22:24.980
Yes, sir.

22:24.980 --> 22:27.220
And he was...

22:27.220 --> 22:30.060
He was my buddy after we met there.

22:30.060 --> 22:31.460
I didn't know who he was.

22:31.460 --> 22:32.460
Right.

22:32.460 --> 22:38.460
He had both legs blown off and he came up to me and put his arm around in Hugmanek.

22:38.460 --> 22:40.460
This was out of a reunion, right?

22:40.460 --> 22:41.460
Right.

22:41.460 --> 22:42.460
He...

22:42.460 --> 22:43.460
Right.

22:43.460 --> 22:48.060
And I don't know where the even new foot outfitties in because we had replacements coming

22:48.060 --> 22:52.500
in all the time.

22:52.500 --> 22:57.140
And you had drug him out of a foxhole and this is the first time that you all have seen

22:57.140 --> 22:59.140
each other since then in 1950.

22:59.140 --> 23:00.140
Right.

23:00.140 --> 23:01.140
So quite a...

23:01.140 --> 23:02.940
Since 1950, right.

23:02.940 --> 23:03.940
He...

23:03.940 --> 23:13.980
He was in that foxhole and there were others wounded and some killed in a martyr attack.

23:13.980 --> 23:20.380
That day we had gone through a small, small village and I got the honor to be sent back to

23:20.380 --> 23:25.380
that village to kick indoors to make sure everybody was out.

23:25.380 --> 23:26.380
Right.

23:26.380 --> 23:33.140
And I think about these guys over in Afghanistan and Iraq that have to kick in those doors

23:33.140 --> 23:35.900
and the chills on up and down my back.

23:35.900 --> 23:36.900
Indeed.

23:36.900 --> 23:43.180
Want to move along because we're running short on time.

23:43.180 --> 23:49.380
You had talked about fighting the Chinese because the North Koreans were pretty much punched

23:49.380 --> 23:53.700
out about this time and fighting the Chinese.

23:53.700 --> 23:58.420
And one thing that you credit really for saving your life during one battle is the World

23:58.420 --> 24:04.660
War II Corsairs and how they provided cover for you in one of the battles in North Korea.

24:04.660 --> 24:12.780
Well, the Marine Corps has an air ground team and on the ground we had flowers that were

24:12.780 --> 24:19.620
farer to observers because they knew how to talk to them in up in these Corsairs.

24:19.620 --> 24:21.020
These were World War II.

24:21.020 --> 24:27.820
It's like everything we had was World War II equipment except later on we had one of

24:27.820 --> 24:32.700
these bubbled helicopters that you see in mash.

24:32.700 --> 24:33.700
Right.

24:33.700 --> 24:34.700
Exactly.

24:34.700 --> 24:39.580
They had put Marines on both wounded on both sides and take them back as fast as they

24:39.580 --> 24:41.220
couldn't and come back.

24:41.220 --> 24:42.220
Right.

24:42.380 --> 24:48.020
You talked about going back, getting on shifts and how those ships had restuffed with

24:48.020 --> 24:53.180
some of what you estimated about 100,000 North Koreans that you took.

24:53.180 --> 24:54.180
Oh, yeah.

24:54.180 --> 24:55.180
Yeah.

24:55.180 --> 25:00.500
That you went to South Korea with you and that the first thing you did when you got back

25:00.500 --> 25:02.820
on the ship was fighting lifeboat to sleep.

25:02.820 --> 25:04.620
You were hungry but sleep was more important.

25:04.620 --> 25:05.620
Right.

25:05.620 --> 25:06.620
I crawled under a lifeboat.

25:06.620 --> 25:10.180
I didn't even go around in that stinking ship.

25:10.180 --> 25:12.660
We found out about this time that you were a corporal.

25:12.660 --> 25:16.820
There was another corporal and only one corporal could go back home and it was you.

25:16.820 --> 25:20.500
The other corporal was a young man with a fellow from Houston.

25:20.500 --> 25:24.660
And they said decide between yourselves which one goes home and which one stays and how

25:24.660 --> 25:25.660
did you do that?

25:25.660 --> 25:27.220
We drew cards.

25:27.220 --> 25:28.220
Somebody had some cards.

25:28.220 --> 25:30.260
I don't know where they came from.

25:30.260 --> 25:31.260
Right.

25:31.260 --> 25:37.900
But I drew a six and a McMahon drew a six.

25:37.900 --> 25:38.900
Right.

25:38.900 --> 25:40.820
And so we had to draw again.

25:40.820 --> 25:47.780
I drew a tin and he drew a jack and he got to go.

25:47.780 --> 25:50.820
And you got to stay and you thought that was in to me.

25:50.820 --> 25:52.660
I would not get out of there.

25:52.660 --> 25:53.660
Right.

25:53.660 --> 25:56.780
But I did about a month later.

25:56.780 --> 25:57.980
I got out.

25:57.980 --> 26:00.100
You got out about a month later.

26:00.100 --> 26:05.300
And so in all your service in Korea was it about eight months, right?

26:05.300 --> 26:06.300
That's right.

26:06.380 --> 26:12.420
I mean, people, they were pulled out first because they had been in constant battle.

26:12.420 --> 26:13.420
Right.

26:13.420 --> 26:19.940
The Korean War was an intense war as you can see from the number of people killed.

26:19.940 --> 26:20.940
Yeah.

26:20.940 --> 26:26.260
You were talking, matter of fact, you brought some numbers there from the chosen reservoir,

26:26.260 --> 26:28.180
the number of killed just from that.

26:28.180 --> 26:29.180
Right.

26:29.660 --> 26:36.060
It was approximately 15,000, 1000 of us up in the reservoir area.

26:36.060 --> 26:41.660
Plus some army that went on the east side of the reservoir.

26:41.660 --> 26:48.500
The 7th regiment and the 5th regiment were sent on up to a place called UDamn-E.

26:48.500 --> 26:52.140
We call it UDamn-E, or didn't get out.

26:52.140 --> 26:57.940
Because the pilots were flying over and they were taking beds.

26:57.940 --> 27:04.260
There's no way that the first marine division was going to get out of that area.

27:04.260 --> 27:05.260
Right.

27:05.260 --> 27:08.660
Got some figures here.

27:08.660 --> 27:14.260
Of course, I mentioned the coal wall ago and the coal would have got as you went out.

27:14.260 --> 27:15.260
Yes, sir.

27:15.260 --> 27:24.580
Approximately seven enemy divisions were wiped out or defeated severely by the first marine

27:24.580 --> 27:27.060
division.

27:27.060 --> 27:29.220
And let me see.

27:29.220 --> 27:37.780
Historians have termed the chosen reservoir campaign, the most savage battle of modern warfare.

27:37.780 --> 27:47.140
President Reagan, cited the chosen campaign, the epic military history.

27:47.140 --> 27:49.820
And so...

27:49.820 --> 27:53.980
No wonder you were such a proud group and a proud organization.

27:53.980 --> 27:54.980
That's correct.

27:54.980 --> 28:01.340
I wish we had time to talk more, but it was such a fantastic service and you are fortunate

28:01.340 --> 28:02.340
to be here.

28:02.340 --> 28:03.340
I got it.

28:03.340 --> 28:04.340
To tell the story.

28:04.340 --> 28:05.340
I got it.

28:05.340 --> 28:06.340
Yes, sir.

28:06.340 --> 28:07.340
A lot of combat.

28:07.340 --> 28:08.340
Thank you very much for your service.

28:08.340 --> 28:09.340
Sure.

28:09.340 --> 28:10.340
And thank you for your time.

28:10.340 --> 28:14.940
Norman Biel and his wife Wanda live in the country with a couple of very friendly dogs.

28:14.940 --> 28:19.780
Norman enjoys his life now that he has well earned by putting his life on the line for

28:19.780 --> 28:24.500
eight months of battling the North Koreans and the Chinese in what they called a forgotten

28:24.500 --> 28:26.100
war, Korea.

28:26.100 --> 28:28.860
But not forgotten to him and certainly not to us.

28:28.860 --> 28:32.500
